<p>The <b>Progressive Era</b> in the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> was a period of reform which lasted from the 1890s to the 1920's.<sup id="cite_ref-women_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-women-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Responding to the changes brought about by industrialization, <sup id="cite_ref-columbia_progressivism_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-columbia_progressivism-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> the <a href="/wiki/Progressives" title="Progressives" class="mw-redirect">Progressives</a> advocated a wide range of economic, political, social, and moral reforms.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> Initially the movement was successful at local level, and then it progressed to state and gradually national. Both the reformers and their opponents were predominantly members of the <a href="/wiki/Middle_class" title="Middle class">middle class</a>.</p>
